    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-02-02T04:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-02-02T04:00:00-05:00" n="273"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d273">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 893.811/245</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Minister <persName type="from">Reinsch</persName> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Peking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-02-02T17:00:00+08:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 2, 1917, 5 p.m</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Japanese newspapers publish a report from New York that the International
                    Corporation proposed to Japanese capitalists to make canal work a joint
                    enterprise and that the Americans have no objection to the Japanese desire to
                    represent the company but that China objects to this. Please inform Straight of
                    this misleading disclosure.</p>
                <pb facs="0376" n="210" xml:id="pg_210"/>
                <p>Initial comment in Chinese papers is extremely unfavorable as they conceive that
                    Americans are guilty of breach of trust and that the object of Japan is to
                    neutralize Chinese distrust by exploiting confidence enjoyed by Americans in
                    China and to fetter freedom of American enterprise.</p>
                <p>The situation is serious and extremely embarrassing to the Legation. It is
                    essential that Corporation should immediately publish true facts as to the
                    source of the original suggestion because the Chinese officials concerned will
                    be questioned on this point.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Reinsch</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
